<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C62FF89FF71FC4CFCE4F20D" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF71FC4CFD23F5BD" blockId="4.[166,717,975,1002]" box="[166,717,975,1002]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
<heading id="6F6881EC6C62FF89FF71FC4CFD23F5BD" box="[166,717,975,1002]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="F39F4D036C62FF89FF71FC4CFEA4F5BD" authorityName="Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1776" box="[166,330,975,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Tyta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luctuosa">
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C62FF89FF71FC4CFEA4F5BD" bold="true" box="[166,330,975,1002]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">Tyta luctuosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
([Denis &amp; Schiffermüller], 1775)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CFC63FCE4F20D" blockId="4.[166,1225,1023,1370]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FDAFFC63FD2AF24D" box="[632,708,1023,1050]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,192,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,192,1690]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Acronictinae: 13–16 — Craniophora ligustri; eggs of Metoponiinae: 17, 18 — Tyta luctuosa. Scale bars: 13, 14, 16–18 — 100 µm; 15 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453288/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 17</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="F3679B656C62FF89FCFCFC63FC69F24D" box="[811,903,1023,1050]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="F3679B656C62FF89FBD4FC63FB61F24D" box="[1027,1167,1023,1050]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.6 mm</quantity>
(n = = 2). Fresh egg pale yellow with black spot at apical part of egg. As egg develops it becomes pale grey and then grey. Chorion white, translucent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C62FF89FF0CFBC3FEBBF30D" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" type="description">
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CFBC3FDA4F34D" blockId="4.[166,1225,1023,1370]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surfaces. Micropylar area represented by clearly expressed rosette and 1 row faintly expressed long, narrow and pointed petalled cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FF79FB03FF12F2ED" box="[174,252,1183,1210]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,192,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,192,1690]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Acronictinae: 13–16 — Craniophora ligustri; eggs of Metoponiinae: 17, 18 — Tyta luctuosa. Scale bars: 13, 14, 16–18 — 100 µm; 15 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453288/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 18</figureCitation>
). Rosette elevated with 9–11 short and wide cells. Walls of cells elevated. (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FBBAFB03FB55F2ED" box="[1133,1211,1183,1210]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 19</figureCitation>
). There are 9–10 of 28–29 clearly expressed longitudinal ridges radiate from cells of first row. Transverse ridges weakly expressed (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FDB6FB43FD32F2AD" box="[609,732,1247,1274]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,192,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,192,1690]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Acronictinae: 13–16 — Craniophora ligustri; eggs of Metoponiinae: 17, 18 — Tyta luctuosa. Scale bars: 13, 14, 16–18 — 100 µm; 15 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453288/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 17–18</figureCitation>
). The entire surface looks like as sharply expressed shallow network (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FE27FB63FDD3F34D" box="[496,573,1279,1306]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CFA83FEBBF30D" blockId="4.[166,1225,1023,1370]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
Shape of gnawed holes in eggs. Caterpillar nibbles out large oval opening at lateral part of egg (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FF2CFAA3FEA9F30D" box="[251,327,1343,1370]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,192,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,192,1690]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Acronictinae: 13–16 — Craniophora ligustri; eggs of Metoponiinae: 17, 18 — Tyta luctuosa. Scale bars: 13, 14, 16–18 — 100 µm; 15 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453288/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 17</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
